After doing some more debugging (i.e. putting hundreds of Log.d calls everywhere in the code), I figured out that removing the `mapView.onDestroy()` stops the issue from happening.

[GoogleMapsController.java:890](https://github.com/flutter/plugins/blob/68cdc58aa67b82209c9eeb832d3e95c9734e3983/packages/google_maps_flutter/google_maps_flutter/android/src/main/java/io/flutter/plugins/googlemaps/GoogleMapController.java#L890)
```java
  private void destroyMapViewIfNecessary() {
    Log.d("ShortyDebug", "destroyMapViewIfNecessary");
    if (mapView == null) {
      return;
    }
    //mapView.onDestroy();
    mapView = null;
    Log.d("ShortyDebug", "destroyMapViewIfNecessary done");
  }
```

I am not quite sure yet, what the downside to this is, but I can imagine that this may cause a memory leak or some other unintended behaviour, since we're basically removing a part of the `dispose()` code.

But atleast now we might have a more concrete idea, which part of the code is destroying something, that is still needed by another part of the code :man_shrugging: 

This is however the part where debugging further gets more complicated, since the destroy call is inside the proprietary code, and decompiling that does not really tell anything too useful. So we might need to get some google engineers involved at this point...

That's indeed quite interesting ... If i wrap the `onDestroy` in a `postFrameCallback` like in the mentioned workaround, the error is also fixed.

```java
postFrameCallback(() -> {
      mapView.onDestroy();
      mapView = null;
});
```

What if the `onDestroy` is called in the wrong order ? I could imagine that there is a check for the status of the mapView (or our mystery array), it assumes it's still valid and uses it for some animation and afterwards the mapView gets destroyed, GCing the array in question. So by adding 1 frame of delay, we signal that stuff is no longer available, said checks notice that and the code using the array is cancelled, after which we can safely GC the array.

I don't quite know how the rendering works here, so I am just trying so extrapolate from the little knowledge of game engine rendering that I have :sweat_smile: 

That being said, the postFrameCallback bandaid seems to work, not produce any jank and still GC the mapview, while not crashing (atleast when i try to cause it in the demo app).

@lukaskurz your code fixes the issues for our app, even with really quick map-switching. 
Good find and good work!

Are you going to make a fork, that can be used until it is officially fixed from "google_maps_flutter" side?
Editing the "GoogleMapsController.java" file is not feasible for a CI setup.

Editing `google_maps_flutter-2.1.8 > android > src > main > java > io > flutter > plugins > googlemaps > GoogleMapsController.java`

Code that works:
```
  private void destroyMapViewIfNecessary() {
    if (mapView == null) {
      return;
    }
    postFrameCallback(() -> {
      mapView.onDestroy();
      mapView = null;
    });
  }
```

Original code that does not work:
```
  private void destroyMapViewIfNecessary() {
    if (mapView == null) {
      return;
    }
    mapView.onDestroy();
    mapView = null;
  }
```

@lukaskurz Thanks for the repository Lukas. I tried to define the `dependency_overrides` within the pubspec.yaml of my package, just to figure out that it will be ignored. You explicitly have to insert it in the pubspec.yaml of the project that consumes my package. Makes sense, because once you remove your repository, my published package would stop to work.

I will inform my users for this temporary fix as of now.

I'm looking forward to a new update from the Google team. I also redirected your fix to the [issue tracker](https://issuetracker.google.com/issues/237380999#comment11) by Google.
